// Constants
c= 3e8; // Speed of light in m/s
mud = 4 * pi * 12-7; 4) Permeability of free space

sigma_cu=5.8e7; — // Conductivity of copper (S/m)

// Input parameters

f= 100e6: // Frequency in Hz (e.g. 100 MHz)
a= 0.05; // Radius of loop in meters
r= 0.001; // Radius of wire in meters (conductor radius)

Hf Derived parameters
lambda=c/f; — // Wavelength
omega = 2 * %pi * f; // Angular frequency

// Radiation resistance (approx for small loop)
Rr = (20 * (mu0%2) * (omega) * (a%4)) / (3 * (c%2));

// Skin depth calculation
delta = sqrt(2 / (omega * mu0 * sigma_cu));

// Resistance per unit length due to skin effect
R_per_length = 1 / (2 * %pi * r * delta * sigma_cu);

// Length of conductor (circumference of loop)
L=2 * %pi * a;

// Loss resistance
RI = R_per_length * L;

// Radiation efficiency
eta = Rr/(Rr+Rl);

// Output

disp("Radiation resistance (Ohms): " + string(Rr));
disp("Loss resistance (Ohms): " + string(Rl));
disp("Radiation efficiency: " + string(eta));

Example Output (for f= 100 MHz, a=5 cm, r= 1 mm):
e Radiation resistance ~ very small (micro-ohms range)

© Loss resistance * a few ohms
¢ Efficiency n « 1 (small loop antennas are inefficient unless optimized)
